<h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Words Ending With -ABLE — Scrabble Suffix Scoring Guide</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mb-6">Published June 15, 2026 · 5 min read</p>

<p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">The -ABLE suffix is one of Scrabble's most versatile endings. It transforms verbs into adjectives (playable, sizable, quotable) and adds 6 base points to any root word. With over 500 valid -ABLE words in SOWPODS, this suffix opens bingo opportunities and lets you extend existing board words for massive scores.</p>

<p>Understanding -ABLE patterns gives you a significant edge in both offensive and defensive play, turning ordinary racks into bingo-scoring powerhouses.</p>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">Why -ABLE Matters in Scrabble</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
  <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">6 pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">A(1)+B(3)+L(1)+E(1) base</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">500+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Valid -ABLE words</p></div>
    <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">5–15</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Letter length range</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<p>The B tile alone contributes 3 points, making -ABLE more valuable than common suffixes like -ED or -ING. Because it attaches to so many roots, you can often extend an opponent's word by hooking -ABLE onto the end for a parallel play.</p>

